	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-DR-19420910_01.jpg"/>
			<p>Dear<persName ref="#ehri_dr_hansen_jakob_hans">Hans Jakob Hansen</persName>,</p>
			<p>Thank you for your kind letter of l.ds. P.J.I.Jr.No. 17.E. Tys.12 / 100, concerning Mrs. Martha Hagen. I understand, that in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2623032/kingdom-of-denmark.html">Danish</placeName> circles, where the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">German</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-815" type="subject">attitude</term> to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-351" type="subject">Jewish question</term> has not yet penetrated, we can
				be somewhat disappointed with the weak results in these cases and tend to think that we are too reluctant on the part of the envoy and
				would, therefore, like to try, as far as possible in a letter, to redress our difficulties.</p>
			<p>The official <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-594" type="subject">German attitude</term> towards the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> gradually becomes more and more severe as
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term> progresses. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> are seen as the enemies of the People and
				they want to get rid of them, at best through isolation in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545"
					type="subject">ghettos</term> in the designated areas. This attitude applies to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> as a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-328" type="subject">race</term> without regard to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1147" type="subject">citizenship</term>, and the goal is the introduction
				of a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-365" type="subject">Jewish law</term> similar to the German
				throughout <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/6255148/europe.html">Europe</placeName>, that is, also in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2623032/kingdom-of-denmark.html">Denmark</placeName>.</p>
			<p>So far, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1149" type="subject">foreign Jews</term> in Germany are
				spared some of the most rigorous <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-951" type="subject">provisions</term>,
				but it is clear that even non-German <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term>, in
				due course, <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-DR-19420910_02.jpg"/> must be <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-182"
					type="subject">anti-nationalsocialist</term>. Both German and foreign <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> were generally allowed to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-880" type="subject">travel</term> earlier - so they could get rid of them
				-, but as the war progressed, another consideration became more and more applicable: The fear of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-220" type="subject">information</term> about conditions in this country
				being spread across <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-213" type="subject">the world</term>, which could
				damage <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1152" type="subject">Germany's</term> position and bring
				substance to the anti-<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-381" type="subject">nationalsocialist</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-986" type="subject">propaganda</term>. It is therefore preferable not to
				see too much traffic across the borders, by persons who are not considered to be 100% <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-367" type="subject">reliable politically</term> – apart from the
				difficulties of permits for entry and exit in general - and for the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864"
					type="subject">Jews</term>, who are all considered 100%-unreliable, we now see an almost completely shut down. While there are
				still exceptions made for foreign <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> it is
				no longer possible for German <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> to travel,
				even if they have acquired foreign <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1147" type="subject"
					>citizenship</term> by <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject">marriage</term>,
				especially when the marriage took place after the introduction of the Jewish law, which is the case both with the married couple Hagen
				and with marriage of Thomsen in Schøn’s letter of <date when="1942-08-01">7 August</date> to Ryder.</p>
			<p>As you know, in the first few years after the introduction of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-335"
					type="subject">Jewish laws</term>, several <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject"
					>female</term> German <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> married
				foreigners. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1176" type="subject">German authorities</term> regard
				all these marriages as concluded solely for trying to circumvent the Jewish laws. In most cases, the motives behind the marriages are
				self-evident (which, of course, does not preclude the man from acting on the noblest and most humane <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-297" type="subject">motives</term>). In addition, according to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1152" type="subject">German</term> opinion, mixing <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryan</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewish</term> blood is a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-365" type="subject">crime</term>, and that <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-375" type="subject">marriages</term> between <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryans</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> are <pb n="3"
					facs="EHRI-DR-19420910_03.jpg"/> forbidden. I, therefore, believe that we are wise to leave these cases as hopeless and save the
				very poor ‘goodwill’ we have for cases about <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2623032/kingdom-of-denmark.html"
					>Danish</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> with Connection to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2623032/kingdom-of-denmark.html">Denmark</placeName>. Even for their part, it can be difficult, since
				the German side expects that the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-948" type="subject">government</term>
				of a neighbouring country shows an <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-815" type="subject"
					>understanding</term> of the German attitude, cf. Minister Mohr's Letter of <date when="1942-04-28">28 April</date> to the
				Director of the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-006627">Ministry of Foreign Affairs</orgName>
				regarding Articles in the ' <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-711" type="subject">Kamptegnet</term> ',
				which in my opinion is very illustrative.</p>
			<p>The way in which you suggest allowing the Consulate General to go to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">police</term> has to be taken with great caution. In
				several cases, the police have <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-277" type="subject">rejected</term> such
				requests from the Consulate General and wanted the issue to go the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-125"
					type="subject">diplomatic</term> way. We have also seen that the police authorities have said to the Consulate General that they
				would have to look after the person if she continued to bother them with applications. We hereby reach a point that I am afraid hasn’t
				had much <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-202" type="subject">attention</term> at home. As a rule, the
				persons seeking our and the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-006627">Ministry of Foreign
					Affairs`</orgName> assistance have tried all possible ways. The result easily becomes an Irritation to the Authorities, which may
				cause fatal consequences for the persons concerned. There is a risk that the authorities, in order to get rid of more nonsense, will
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">send</term> those concerned to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1191" type="subject">General Government</term> or to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-places-place-iti-29">Theresienstadt</placeName>. Furthermore, there is the
				risk of 1) that the relatively gentle treatment of foreign <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864"
					type="subject">Jews</term> in part is replaced by a sharper course and 2) that the question of precautionary <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-542" type="subject">measures</term> against <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jews</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2623032/kingdom-of-denmark.html">Denmark</placeName> becomes relevant. After all, <pb n="4"
					facs="EHRI-DR-19420910_04.jpg"/> it is of no use that <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2623032/kingdom-of-denmark.html"
					>Denmark</placeName> becomes more famous than most necessary as a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewish</term> sanctuary. I, therefore, allow you to
				recommend that you explain to Mr. Hagen, that by pushing more on applications for the wife's exit permit, as well as through us as
				directly to the German authorities, will risk doing her more harm than good.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_dr_steensen-leth_vincens">Vincens Steensen-Leth</persName></p>
